<h2>Purpose</h2>
<p>
  Grounds decision
  <a href="/backlog/2077-parallel-orchestrator-exclude-self-modifying-items-from-conc/">#2077</a> —
  what is the standing rule for <strong>self-modifying items</strong>: backlog items whose touch-set includes
  the <code>/workflow</code> parallel run's <em>own</em> executing tooling (the orchestrator workflow script,
  the batch skill, and the scripts the run shells out to mid-run)?
</p>

<h2>The incident (in-repo grounding)</h2>
<p>
  Run <code>batch-2026-07-01-1947-2071</code> TaskStop'd after #2073's lane wedged editing the live
  orchestrator file (<code>parallel-execute.workflow.js</code>, sandbox-locked while the Workflow tool
  executed it): 5 of 17 items landed; 12 pre-claimed items were reopened by hand (commit
  <code>34a26a39</code>). #2071/#2072/#2073 all edited the executing file. The wedge is structural under the
  current substrate: the serial lane works items <em>in place in the primary checkout</em>, and the
  integrator merges every concurrent lane ref <em>into the primary</em> mid-run — so both in-run routes end
  in a write to the file the run is executing.
</p>
<ul>
  <li>The partition has no predicate for this hazard class: <code>conflicts()</code> is strictly pairwise,
    and the <code>RESERVED_MERGE_RISK_BY_REPO</code> denylist guards a different failure (clean-but-wrong
    merges between two items). A <em>lone</em> self-modifying item runs concurrent unflagged.</li>
  <li>Recurrence is structural: the orchestrator file carries 20+ resolve commits (its feature history lands
    as edits to itself), and the #2086 mirror pattern means orchestrator items touch both the canonical
    module in <code>scripts/readiness/</code> and the inline sandbox mirror.</li>
</ul>

<h2>What later rulings changed</h2>
<p>
  The #2138 rider (<em>pr-flow-rollout-mechanism</em>) rules that every lane-producing session stops at
  lane-push and never touches <code>main</code>, with a human-drained queue landing later; #2123 rules every
  edit-action session runs in an isolated lane clone. In that ratified steady state no write hits the primary
  checkout during a producing run — the hazard is <strong>substrate-conditional</strong>: real under today's
  in-run integrator, structurally dissolved once the #2138 substrate (#2151/#2152/#2153) is built.
</p>

<h2>External prior art</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>GitHub Actions</strong> pins the run's workflow definition at run start (the triggering
    commit's version); a mid-run push to the workflow file never re-configures a live run — the change takes
    effect on the next run.</li>
  <li><strong>Jenkins</strong> pins shared-pipeline-library versions per run; pipeline-as-code changes apply
    to subsequent builds.</li>
  <li><strong>Merge bots (bors lineage)</strong> manage a repository from a deployment <em>outside</em> the
    tree they land — changes to the bot's own code ride the normal queue and take effect on redeploy, never
    mid-batch.</li>
</ul>
<p>
  The uniform pattern: <em>never mutate the executing pipeline definition mid-run; let the tooling change
  land like any other change and take effect next run.</em>
</p>

<h2>Synthesis — the prepared forks</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Fork 1 (detection):</strong> a declared <code>RUN_TOOLING</code> pathspec in the canonical,
    tested <code>scripts/readiness/lane-partition.mjs</code> (+ inline sandbox mirror), matched against the
    probe's predicted touch-set in Phase 1 <em>before</em> the Phase-2 pre-claim. Skeptic-amended guard
    completeness: a post-hoc seat over each lane's reported <code>changedFiles</code> at integrate time
    (probes under-report), a hard serial-lane prompt guard (the probe-failed-and-undeclared residual), and a
    <em>coverage-parity unit test</em> that derives the workflow's shell-out set from its source and asserts
    the declared list covers it (the list is itself fails-open on drift, and the post-hoc seat shares the
    pathspec). A per-item frontmatter flag fails open on omission; a loader/engine
    <code>batchable:false</code> over-excludes (the same pack feeds serial <code>/batch</code>, where the
    item is safe).</li>
  <li><strong>Fork 2 (routing):</strong> today a flagged item is dropped from the <code>/workflow</code> run
    at probe time and worked <em>solo, or as the last item of a serial</em> <code>/batch</code> (mid-batch
    edits to shelled run-tooling create the same mixed-version condition); the exclusion carries a concrete
    sunset — once the #2153 drain is live and the in-run integrator/serial lane retire onto the queue, a
    self-modifying item may run in a concurrent lane and land via the drain (an <em>entailment of the #2138
    rider</em>, cited rather than re-ruled). Drain-era residual: the drain is itself a live run that shells
    out to <code>RUN_TOOLING</code>, so it lands such items last (or as a dedicated final pass). The in-run
    serial lane is the rejected, observed-broken branch. Codifies as a rider under
    <em>pr-flow-rollout-mechanism</em>, never a new anchor.</li>
  <li><strong>Dissolved:</strong> the card's "move the tooling to an editable locus" option — the movable
    logic already moved (the #2086 canonical-module pattern); the executing file is executed by path, so
    relocation does not stop it being the executing file. Snapshot-execute (the GitHub-Actions pin) is the
    named fallback only if the #2138 substrate slips indefinitely.</li>
</ul>

